# Core Memory Registry Review

## Purpose

Core Memory Registry Review defines how Dreaming Mode outputs become reviewed memory candidates and, when appropriate, canonical project knowledge.

Dreaming Mode does not automatically write canonical memory.

## Promotion Flow

```text
Dreaming Output
→ Memory Candidate
→ Review / Classification
→ Approved Canonical Candidate
→ Core Registry Update Proposal
→ Agent Context Refresh
```

## Review Inputs

Core reviewers may consider:

- Agent Local Dream outputs;
- Nucleus Dream outputs;
- ACS Global Dream Digest;
- sprint reports;
- Core Registry references;
- Governance and security policies;
- explicitly confirmed project-owner decisions.

## Canonical Promotion Criteria

A candidate may be promoted only if it is:

- stable;
- approved or repeatedly confirmed;
- useful across sessions;
- non-secret;
- non-temporary;
- non-speculative;
- aligned with Axodus architecture;
- assigned to a clear owner;
- traceable to source context.

## Rejection Reasons

Reject or downgrade candidates that are:

- too temporary;
- insufficiently sourced;
- duplicated;
- speculative;
- sensitive or secret-bearing;
- obsolete;
- nucleus-local only;
- contradicted by Core/Governance policy;
- based only on noisy runtime logs.

## Review Output

Core Memory Review should produce:

- approved canonical candidates;
- rejected candidates;
- conflicts requiring human review;
- suggested Core Registry changes;
- suggested agent context updates;
- confidence assessment.

## Canonical Update Proposal

For each approved candidate, include:

- statement;
- owner;
- affected nuclei;
- source context;
- reason for promotion;
- suggested registry or `.instructions` location;
- confidence;
- required approval, if any.

## Agent Context Refresh

After Core review, agents may refresh local context from approved outputs only.

Agent refresh must:

- preserve Core as source of truth;
- avoid importing rejected candidates;
- keep nucleus-local facts scoped;
- discard expired ephemeral/session notes;
- never import secrets or raw sensitive logs.

## Human Review Triggers

Require human review when:

- a candidate changes architecture;
- a candidate affects governance, treasury, trading, security, or production boundaries;
- sources conflict;
- ownership is unclear;
- a candidate may alter canonical terminology;
- a candidate may affect multiple nuclei;
- promotion could authorize future automation.

## Security Requirements

Core Memory Review must never promote:

- secrets;
- private keys;
- wallet seed phrases;
- credentials;
- auth headers;
- API tokens;
- raw production logs;
- unredacted user/device identifiers;
- speculative security assumptions.

## Final Rule

Core memory is a governed source of truth. Dreaming outputs are inputs to review, not authority.
